<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Convergence Backs AD's Empowering Bill Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2403154994 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2403154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] National Convergence [CN] supports Democratic 
Action's [AD] empowering bill proposal which gives special 
powers to the executive to sign into law a tax package presented 
at Congress. CN coordinator Jose Miguel Uzcategui said the party 
has already told the president their position. He also said, 
however, that CN legislation experts have studied the empowering 
bill proposed by AD and have found that financial and economic 
outlines, which should have been included in the proposal, are 
missing. He also said that analysts have been looking into past 
experiences with previous empowering laws, particularly those 
during former President Ramon J. Velasquez' time when he was 
forced to apply measures, like the value-added tax, on consumers. 
  [Begin Uzcategui recording] Additionally, we must discuss 
the 
temporary nature of the law. Three of the previous experiences 
lasted one year each and the last one lasted five months. We 
believe some decrees can be drafted and enacted in 30 days. This 
period of time, however, is too short for fiscal measures. [end 
recording] 
  Finally, Uzcategui said it is the president which must 
decide 
on an empowering bill, providing the president is familiar with 
the bill's definitive wording. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11728 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat058_c_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-058 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chretien Meets With Leaders, Expresses Confidence </TI></H3>
<H4>   To Continue Investments </H4>
<F P=102> PA2503154594 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
1300 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2503154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ivonne Romero; from the "Upon Awakening" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien said today 
Canada will continue to negotiate and invest in Mexico despite 
the tragic death of Luis Donaldo Colosio Murrieta, presidential 
candidate of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, on 23 March. 
  [Begin Chretien recording, in English] We must not allow 
violence to prevail. We must not give in to democracy's 
enemies. We must not allow this tragic event to turn back the 
clock of democracy and economic progress in Mexico. [end 
recording] 
  During a news conference in Mexico City, the Canadian prime 
minister explained he met with President Carlos Salinas de 
Gortari at Los Pinos on Wednesday evening. He said they both 
agreed the development of democracy and economic opportunities 
must continue. 
  Chretien also issued an invitation to Mexican and foreign 
businessmen. 
  [Begin Chretien recording, in English] You must not let last 
night's tragedy change your plans to do business in Mexico. 
Keep investing in this country, keep building the Mexican 
economy, keep working toward a more open and democratic society. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

