<H3> <TI>   Camacho Solis Denies Plans To Run for Office </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2403233894 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 2231 
GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2403233894 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Amid rivers of human beings that inundated Felix 
Cuevas Avenue and the streets near the funeral home where a wake 
was held for the remains of Luis Donaldo Colosio Murrieta, 
Manuel Camacho Solis, peace and reconciliation commissioner for 
Chiapas, gave his condolences to the relatives of the 
Institutional Revolutionary Party candidate. He captured the 
attention of political representatives and the media who were 
standing outside the funeral home. 
  Camacho Solis was asked about the incidents of violence in 
Tijuana, Baja California. He gave a brief message to the public. 
  [Begin Camacho Solis recording] I wanted to be present here 
publicly because my position has always been an open one. The 
things I have always wanted to do have always been open. I 
deeply regret what has happened. It is something very serious 
for the country's life. Before the eyes of the nation I want to 
make the following statement: Two days ago I said I did not seek 
to be president of the republic. After the incidents that have 
taken place, after this tremendous attack on the nation, I 
reiterate what I have already said. I do not aspire to be 
president of the republic. The fatherland is above everything 
and above everyone. [end recording] 
  [Hamburg DPA in Spanish at 2024 GMT on 24 March transmits a 
180-word report datelined Mexico City stating that "a crowd of 
Colosio's supporters today protested the presence of Manuel 
Camacho Solis, principal rival of the slain candidate for the 
Mexican ruling party's presidential nomination, when he appeared 
at the wake in a mortuary in this capital. 
  "Camacho, who declined to speak to reporters, arrived this 
morning in Mexico City from Tuxtla Gutierrez, capital of the 
southern state of Chiapas, where he had been flown in a military 
helicopter from San Cristobal de las Casas, seat of the peace 
negotiations with the Zapatist Indian organization."] 

