<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bishop Says Chiapas Conflict Continues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2403071194 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2403071194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Monsignor Samuel Ruiz, bishop of San Cristobal de 
las Casas, today attended a social medicine congress in 
Guadalajara and discussed the situation in Chiapas. 
  The military conflict in Chiapas has not ended. The fact 
that a cease-fire was achieved and a first round of talks has 
started does not mean the Zapatist National Liberation Army 
[EZLN] will lay down its weapons. They expect the agreements 
will be signed, it was stated in Guadalajara by Msgr. Ruiz, who 
added that the war is still on. 
  [Begin Ruiz recording] Perhaps it is believed the war has 
ended so it is not visualized. There is a war, there is a 
cease-fire, and there was a mutual determination -- although not 
in writing yet -- to gather forces where they are right now, 
without subsequent mobilization. A dialogue has started but no 
peace accords have been signed yet. However, this has been 
forgotten in the country. [end recording] 
  He said the Chiapas conflict is the shortest war in the 
world 
and the one which resulted in a dialogue the fastest. Msgr. 
Samuel Ruiz arrived in Guadalajara for the Sixth Latin American 
Congress on Social Medicine, during which he questioned the 
health aid given to socialist countries like Cuba. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

