<H3> <TI>   German Party Delegation Visits Santiago de Cuba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2603130294 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0003 
GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2603130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the invitation of the Communist Party of Cuba a 
delegation of the Social Democratic Party from northern Hessen, 
Germany, is visiting Cuba. They have held extensive meetings to 
become familiarized with current situation in Cuba. (Ernest 
Whasthle), member of the presidency of the committee of the 
party and senator of the Federal German Parliament, gave his 
opinion on the blockade that for more than three decades the 
United States has imposed on Cuba: 
  [Begin (Whasthle) recording in German with 
passage-by-passage 
translation into Spanish] Our delegation agrees that this 
embargo should be eliminated in the interest of the Cuban 
people, and we will do everything we can to contribute to the 
lifting of the U.S. embargo. However, we must stress that we do 
not have enough pull to influence the decisions made by the U.S. 
Government. 
  However, I can say that we agree with the many groups, some 
of which are in the United States, that think the embargo should 
be eliminated. [end recording] 
  The Social Democratic Party delegation from northern Hessen 
visited Santiago de Cuba Province where they held meetings and 
talks to strengthen future relations. 
  [Begin (Whasthle) recording in German with 
passage-by-passage translation into Spanish] We selected 
Santiago de Cuba for our meetings for a definite reason. This 
region and ours have similar structures. We have conducted a 
very broad and constructive political dialogue. This dialogue 
should be continued at the provincial level. We also expect that 
our visit serves to encourage the Social Democratic Party to 
establish ties at a higher level. [end recording] 
  During their stay, the delegation visited several 
institutions and economic and social centers of interest, which 
will allow them to have a panoramic view of the current Cuban 
situation. 

</TEXT>

