<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Governor Denies Disruption of Peace Process </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2703135494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0930 GMT 27 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2703135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tuxtla Gutierrez, Chiapas State, 27 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- 
Chiapas State Governor Javier Lopez Moreno has denied the 
Zapatist National Liberation Army's (EZLN) "state of alert" is 
disrupting the peace process in the region. In remarks to the 
local press, he added the state government, which he heads, and 
the federal government will continue their steadfast efforts to 
promote and reach peace. 
  The EZLN, the governor has said, has respected the 
cease-fire. Bishop Manuel Ruiz, mediator of the Chiapas 
conflict, said on 26 March in San Cristobal de las Casas, the 
site of the peace talks between the EZLN and the federal 
government, the Zapatists' decision to halt the consultations 
and declare a state of alert responds to the country's 
prevailing situation. He added the date for the second peace 
talks has not been set yet. 
  The Zapatists, according to the communique issued 25 March 
and carried by the local and foreign media, came in the wake of 
the murder of Luis Donaldo Colosio, presidential candidate of 
the Institutional Revolutionary Party, on 23 March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

