<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Camacho: Government Backs Peace Process </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2703000094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2152 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2703000094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 26 Mar (EFE) -- Manuel Camacho Solis, 
the commissioner for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas, 
reported in a press release today, Saturday, that the Mexican 
Government and Army support the political negotiations and the 
peace process in resolving the armed conflict. 
  Camacho replied to charges made by the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army (EZLN) that the government was preparing an 
imminent attack against EZLN positions and had bombed an area 
close to the southern city of Comitan, approximately 1,200 km 
from Mexico City. 
  Camacho said he had sent a confidential communique to the 
EZLN on its main military concerns to clarify the current 
situation in the Chiapas conflict zone. 
  The peace commissioner asserted that despite the tense 
situation in Chiapas over the past weeks, both the Mexican Army 
and the EZLN had respected the truce and had complied with the 
agreed upon cease-fire. 
  The document signed by Manuel Camacho stated: "The dialogue 
and political negotiations halted the war and opened 
possibilities for an agreement, and this continues to be the 
only way to find a dignified peace in Chiapas." 
  The murder of Luis Donaldo Colosio, the presidential 
candidate of the Institutional Revolutionary party (PRI), 
prompted a situation of political uncertainty regarding the 
peace process and presidential succession. The EZLN said the 
PRI candidate's murder was a cowardly act and announced that its 
forces would be on red alert to counter an imminent attack from 
government forces, which it accused of increasing their military 
presence and preparing a military offensive. 
  The Zapatists accused the hard-line sectors and supporters 
of 
the military for the bloodshed in the country, Colosio's murder, 
and attempts to annul all peaceful efforts to democratize Mexico. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

