<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Marcos Comments on Colosio Murder </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2603003994 Monterrey EL NORTE (Foreign Edition) in Spanish 
25 Mar 94 p 24A </F>

<F P=103> PA2603003994 </F>
<F P=104>  Monterrey EL NORTE (Foreign Edition) </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Juan Manuel Alvarado] </F>
  [Text] Lacandona Jungle, (APRO) [expansion unknown] -- 
Subcommander Marcos, spokesperson for the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army [EZLN], said that the only ones to gain from the 
murder of Luis Donaldo Colosio [Mexican Institutional 
Revolutionay Party, PRI, presidential candidate] are those 
pressure groups that are opposed to peace. Monsignor Samuel 
Ruiz, the bishop of San Cristobal de las Casas, warned of the 
danger of destabilization. 
  In an interview on the night of 23 March on the outskirts of 
a town in the Lacandona Jungle, Marcos said that "at the 
beginning Colosio was a sure thing to be elected for Carlos 
Salinas de Gortari's position. However, he began to change his 
discourse and his line of action. The ruling pressure groups who 
have always opposed the peace talks in Chiapas are the ones who 
gain from this action. The EZLN loses, mediator Samuel Ruiz 
loses, and peace Commissioner Manuel Camacho Solis loses." 
  He explained that the country now faces a crisis, not only 
within the PRI campaign but also within all the other parties, 
which will now have to redefine their strategies. Marcos said 
the upcoming political changes were the result of the 1 January 
armed uprising. He said the Colosio he saw on the campaign trail 
was always wise in addressing the EZLN. "He never spoke of us as 
criminals. As I see it, he had begun to steer away from the 
Salinas strategies. He was trying to draft his own ideas and to 
recognize that there are in fact very deep social problems. The 
Zapatists had seen the face of Salinas de Gortari in the PRI 
presidential candidate -- the same economic plan with the same 
political ties and similar social cost," Marcos said. "But he 
had tried to change that. We do not know what will happen now 
that he has died." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

