<H3> <TI>   Extra Security for Presidential Candidates </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2603215694 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1933 GMT 26 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2603215694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 26 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Mexico City Mayor 
Manuel Aguilera Gomez today announced that additional steps are 
being taken to bolster security for presidential candidates 
while they campaign in the capital. The additional measures are 
designed to help guarantee the candidates' personal safety. 
  "There will be more (police) units at the political events 
they (the candidates) attend," Aguilera told reporters. "Some 
have accepted this, but others, such as Diego Fernandez de 
Cevallos, the presidential candidate of the conservative 
National Action Party, oppose the move. I believe it would be 
desirable if they all would agree to accept the additional 
security." 
  The move was ordered in the wake of the assassination of 
Luis 
Donaldo Colosio, the presidential candidate of the Institutional 
Revolutionary Party (PRI) who was killed at a political event in 
Tijuana in northern Mexico on Wednesday. All eight opposition 
candidates participating in the presidential elections scheduled 
for 21 August have condemned Colosio's murder. 

</TEXT>

