<H3> <TI>   Chamber of Deputies Urges Avoiding Speculation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2503204894 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1949 
GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2503204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Luis Sarmiento from the Chamber of Deputies </F>
in Mexico City] 
  [Text] No one should speculate, so that the economic and 
political problems in the country do not worsen. This statement 
was made by Gonzalo Altamirano Dimas, a deputy from the National 
Action Party [PAN] and party president in the Federal District. 
He added that although the Mexican Stock Exchange [BMV] has 
experienced some drops, this is something natural due to the 
recent murder of Luis Donaldo Colosio. In an interview, Gonzalo 
Altamirano Dimas said that the stability of the BMV will depend 
on immediate actions by the authorities. 
  [Begin Altamirano Dimas recording] We must be prudent, the 
country's interests must prevail over all other interests, 
regardless of how legitimate these may be. The death of Mr. 
Colosio must be cleared up. We join this clamor for a thorough 
investigation and that the persons responsible for the attack be 
arrested and punished with the full weight of the law. [end 
recording] 
  Meanwhile, the parliamentary group of the Party of the 
Democratic Revolution [PRD] has also rejected all ties with 
violence. In a news conference, the PRD wing at the Chamber of 
Deputies sent condolences to the family of Luis Donaldo Colosio 
Murrieta. The party demanded a thorough investigation and 
clarification of the presidential candidate's murder. 
  PRD Deputy Alejandro Encinas announced the commission to 
investigate the attack on Luis Donaldo Colosio has begun to work 
and will be in Tijuana early Saturday morning to meet with the 
highest federal authorities, study the area where Colosio was 
killed, and prepare a detailed report that will be presented on 
Monday to the Permanent Commission of the Congress. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

