<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Private Sector Guarantees No Change in Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2503153794 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2503153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Mexican private sector has guaranteed that the 
violent events that led to the death of Luis Donaldo Colosio 
will not change the economic course of the nation nor will they 
provoke flight of capital or depreciation of the peso. The 
reason for this is because Mexico has solid instruments for 
confronting possible alterations in the financial markets. 
  [Begin unidentified entrepreneur recording] We feel that we 
have a solid project, particularly if we all defend it. [end 
recording] 
  The entrepreneur pointed out that an emergency plan is not 
needed, nor any additional measures other than the ones agreed 
upon in the current agreement. Nonetheless, he warned that we 
must be very cautious and not allow strange forces to manipulate 
us and alter the economic and political program or even lead to 
destabilization. 
  [Begin Antonio Sanchez Diaz de Rivera, president of Mexican 
Employers Confederation, recording] Some are trying to attain 
that destabilization. Nonetheless, if all sectors are united 
and there is social unity, and if authorities and society act 
jointly to prevent it, we will definitely prevent it. [end 
recording] 
  In matters of politics, the businessmen pointed out that 
although the death of the PRI [Institutional Revolutionary 
Party] presidential candidate will somewhat tarnish the 
electoral process, they ruled out the possibility that the 
elections be postponed beyond 21 August. 
  [Begin Ricardo Dajer Nahum, president of Confederation of 
National Chambers of Commerce, recording] I think the elections 
must be held on 21 August. I feel we cannot allow the 
objectives of those who have provoked a series of events -- that 
we denounced in a certain way last week -- to be attained. [end 
recording] 
  As for the financial markets that remain closed on Thursday 
as a sign of mourning, Manuel Robleda, leader of the Mexican 
Stock Market, urged investors to be prudent, as it was observed 
in the foreign market that Mexican Government debt titles 
registered a moderate drop. 
  Throughout the financial institutions, the polled 
businessmen 
said they were determined to continue working for the benefit of 
the economic project. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified businessman] The economy 
must 
remain at the same level it is now. It must maintain the same 
standards of living we have and continue working as usual. 
  [Second unidentified businessman] There will not be any 
movements that will change our country's way of living. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

