<H3> <TI>   More International Reaction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2503163894 </F>
<F P=103> PA2503163894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
international reaction to the 23 March assassination in Tijuana, 
Baja California, of Luis Donaldo Colosio Murrieta, presidential 
candidate for the Mexican Institutional Revolutionary Party, PRI. 
  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish at 1600 GMT on 24 
March broadcasted a one-minute report on a fax received from 
Nobel Prize winner Rigoberta Menchu expressing her consternation 
on and rejection of the attack on Colosio. 
  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish at 1600 on 24 
March 
also broadcasted a one-minute report on U.N. Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali repudiating the attack on Colosio. 
Butrus-Ghali adds that he deplores any form of violence. 
  Panama City ACAN at 1904 GMT on 24 March carried a 150-word, 
Panama City-datelined report on the Christian Democratic 
Organization of America's, ODCA, rejecting Colosio's murder. 
The ODCA, which is holding a meeting in Panama, expressed in a 
communique their hope that "this regrettable incident will not 
adversely affect the electoral process and the modernization of 
the Mexican political system." 
  Managua Radio Nicaragua in Spanish at 1200 GMT on 24 March 
broadcasted a two-minute report on a press communique issued by 
Violeta Chamorro's government rejecting the "brutal" murder of 
Luis Donaldo Colosio. The communique goes on to rule out any 
violent method that brings mourning to the Mexican people and to 
the whole world. 
  Madrid EFE in Spanish at 1016 GMT on 24 March carried a 
200-word, Havana-datelined item reporting Cuban President Fidel 
Castro's "consternation, pain, and repudiation" upon learning 
the death of PRI candidate Colosio. The item reports that 
Castro sent a message of condolence to Mexican President Carlos 
Salinas de Gortari. 
  Hamburg DPA at 2121 GMT on 24 March carried a 650-word, 
Buenos Aires/Mexico City-datelined roundup of unanimous regional 
consternation over Colosio's murder. 
  According the DPA roundup, Brazilian President Itamar Franco 
rejected the "absurd and shocking act of violence" that led to 
Colosio's death. 
  Argentine President Carlos Menem said he "was profoundly 
moved by the tragic death" of the PRI candidate, and he 
expressed hope that "acts of vandalism and terrorism will soon 
be overcome in our community of nations." 
  Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera sent a message to his 
Mexican counterpart expressing his "total shock" upon learning 
of Colosio's murder, noting that Mexico is going through "sad 
and difficult times." 
  The DPA roundup noted Chilean President Eduardo Frei's 
"condemnation and rejection" of the murder. Frei sent his 
expressions of "regret and solidarity" to his Mexican 
counterpart, Salinas de Gortari. 
  Costa Rican President Rafael Caldera's warned that this 
murder is an "act against democracy" in Mexico and in Latin 
America. 
  The Honduran Government issued a communique rejecting 
violence as a method to solving political problems. 
  Panamanian President Guillermo Endara was "pained" to learn 
of Colosio's death. 
  At 2155 GMT, Panama City ACAN carried a 150-word, San 
Jose-datelined report that Oscar Arias, Nobel Peace Prize and 
former Panamanian president, said today that Colosio's death "is 
a cause of concern for the Americas. It is important now that 
calm, level-headedness, and national unity prevail, that the 
important Mexico that we know should not throw itself into 
despair and disorder," Arias added. 
  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish at 2135 GMT on 24 
March carried a two-minute report noting that Brian Mulroney, 
former Canadian prime minister, labeled the incident in Baja 
California as "a cowardly political assassination against 
Mexico's democracy, perpetrated for reasons that are truly trite 
and irrational." 
  Madrid EFE in Spanish at 2124 GMT on 24 March carried a 
1,200-word, Madrid-datelined roundup of reaction to PRI 
candidate Colosio's murder. 
  Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon Carpio said that with 
his 
death, Colosio's "political message takes on a greater meaning 
and makes it more legitimate and pure as an example for all 
democratic sectors." 
  Dominican Republican President Joaquin Balaguer expressed in 
a letter to President Salinas his "solidarity and sincere 
expressions of regret and sorrow." 
  EFE notes that an Uruguay Foreign Ministry communique said 
Colosio's murder is "one more expression of political 
intolerance and barbarity that adversely affects not only the 
right to life but also the basic principles on which democracy 
supports its existence and stability." 
  The Bolivian president sent a message that, according to 
Foreign Minister Antonio Aranibar, "expresses his sorrow to the 
Colosio family, the Mexican Government and people." 
  Guatemalan national Alfredo Skinner-Klee, acting president 
of 
the Central American Parliament, said: "These acts of violence 
only contribute to the deterioration of the democratic process 
and the opening of new wounds of resentment." 
  Enrique Iglesias, Inter-American Development Bank president, 
commented that Colosio's murder "hurts the Mexican nation and 
the democratic consciousness of all Latin America." 
  Manuel Fraga, chief of the Galicia Regional Government in 
Spain, expressed his "profound condolence for and firm 
rejection" of such a "vile assassination" in a telegram to 
Mexican President Salinas. 
  Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish at 2153 GMT on 24 March 
carried a 500-word, Paris-datelined item which reports on a 
message sent by Philippe Seguin, acting president of the 91st 
Parliamentary Conference being held in Paris. Seguin said: "In 
my name and that of my colleagues we express our sympathy for 
the Mexican delegation and once again we underline our absolute 
rejection of electoral violence." 
  The NOTIMEX item also noted that in Madrid, Spanish Foreign 
Minister Javier Solana labeled Colosio's murder as "terrible." 
At a news conference, Felipe Gonzalez, president of the Spanish 
Government, expressed his pain for the crime and reiterated his 
solidarity with the Mexican Government. The ruling Spanish 
Labor Party, in a communique labeled Colosio's murder as "a 
criminal act, the sole goal of which is to absurdly hamper the 
Mexican electoral process." 
  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 
at 0000 GMT on 25 March carried a 1-minute report which noted 
that Colombian presidential candidate Ernesto Samper sent a 
letter to Mexican President Salinas de Gortari recalling his 
meeting with Colosio four months ago. The same report noted 
reaction by Andres Pastrana, presidential candidate for the 
Colombian New Democratic Force, and by presidential hopeful 
Miguel Maza Marquez. Maza is quoted as saying: "Yesterday it 
was the incident in Chiapas, now this assassination; the result 
of intolerance." Pastrana is quoted as saying: "It is very 
regrettable to see how our democracy is being murdered, that is, 
Latin American democracy." 
  Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish at 2300 GMT 
on 
24 March carried a one-minute report on Ernesto Perez 
Balladares, presidential candidate for the Panamanian Democratic 
Revolutionary Party, who told RPC that he hopes that incidents 
of this nature will not be repeated any other place. 
  The same report adds that Arturo Vallarino, president of the 
Panamanian Legislative Assembly, repudiated Colosio's murder 
noting: "A shot has been fired not only at a candidate but at 
democracy." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

