<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2403220994 </F>
<F P=103> PY2403220994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Peru monitored through 24 
March. 
  Eurobonds have become a good alternative for Peruvian 
companies that need to obtain financing without paying the high 
interest rates charged by the local financial system. Companies 
must pay those who buy the bonds an average interest rate of 8 
to 10 percent per year to obtain the disbursement almost 
immediately. The Arias Group's La Poderosa mine was the first 
company to issue Eurobonds. It obtained a 10.75 percent profit 
in one year from the sale of $6 million worth of Eurobonds 
issued in December 1993. The Rodriguez Banda Group's Gloria 
company and the Tele2000 company will issue $40 million each in 
Eurobonds in March. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 9 Mar 94 p A24) 
  National Mining Association President Roque Benavides Ganoza 
expects the mining sector to attract $7 billion in investment in 
the next five years. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 12 Mar 94 p A26) 
  After six years, the French Government has decided to renew 
trade guarantees for Peruvian exports to France. The French 
Insurance Company for Foreign Trade has guaranteed short-term 
exports valued at approximately $3.5 million, which could grow 
to $9.5 million in 1995. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 11 Mar 94 p 
A24) 
  A Mining and Energy Ministry source reported that gold 
production increased 12 percent in 1993, after the Yanacocha 
mining processing plant began operation. Production totalled 
57,603 troy ounces in January, 6 percent more than in the same 
month last year. (Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 11 Mar 94 B1) 
  The Central Reserve Bank's net international reserves 
reached 
a record $3.46 billion through 18 February, an increase of $260 
million compared with the previous week. (Lima EL PERUANO in 
Spanish 11 Mar 94 p B2) 
  On 15 March, the Mining and Energy Ministry reported that 
average oil production was 130,763 barrels per day in the 
January-February period, higher than the same months in 1993 
when it was 123,440 barrels. The ministry expects average oil 
production in 1994 to be 132,000 barrels per day. (Lima EL 
PERUANO in Spanish 16 Mar 94 p B3) 
  The Andean Development Corporation approved credits of up 
$140 million for Peru. They will be used to implement programs 
for small enterprises and highway development projects. (Lima EL 
COMERCIO in Spanish 16 Mar 94 p 1) 
  Japan granted Peru a $21 million loan to finance health 
programs. It also will donate equipment worth $180,000 for 
people affected by floods. (Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 16 Mar 94 
p 1) 
  During the 15 March congressional session, Economy Minister 
Jorge Camet, Agriculture Minister Absalon Vasquez, and 
representatives of the Democratic Constituent Congress 
Agriculture Committee declared that the agricultural sector has 
been in a state of emergency for approximately two years in the 
wake of floods and plagues affecting the countryside. (Lima EL 
PERUANO in Spanish 16 Mar 94 p B1) 
  Peruvian and Chilean entrepreneurs formed a joint venture 
for 
the exclusive commercialization of Volkswagen cars in Peru with 
an $18 million investment. The Chilean economic group Matisse 
will provide 40 percent of the capital and the Peruvian 
investors 60 percent. (Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 17 Mar 94 p B2) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

