<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian President Elected OAS Secretary General </TI></H3>
<H4>   Central Americans Back Costa Rica's Niehaus </H4>
<F P=102> PA2603021894 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2603021894 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The "24 Hours Newscast" consulted some Central 
American foreign ministries -- that allegedly support Bernd 
Niehaus [Costa Rican foreign minister] -- on the candidate for 
whom they intend to vote in the election for secretary general 
of the Organization of American States. Some of the Central 
American officials charged that they are being pressured by the 
United States to change their vote. 
  The first country consulted was Costa Rica, home of Foreign 
Minister Niehaus -- President Cesar Gaviria's closest rival. 
Here they are already claiming victory. 
  [Begin recording] [Jose Joaquin Chaberry, unidentified Costa 
Rican official] We are certain we will win. We are very certain 
of this. We have reiterated this during the past months and the 
past days.... 
  [Unidentified reporter, interrupting] But do you believe 
pressure is being exerted? 
  [Chaberry] I repeat Foreign Minister Niehaus' words: If 
there 
is pressure, we will report it. [end recording] 
  El Salvador maintains its position to support Niehaus, 
although Deputy Foreign Minister Rafael Alfaro said they are 
being pressured to favor President Cesar Gaviria. 
  [Begin recording] [Alfaro] We continue, nevertheless, with 
our firm support for Foreign Minister Niehaus. 
  [Reporter] Mr. Deputy Foreign Minister, is it true that 
there 
has been pressure on the part of the U.S. Government on the 
Central American nations? 
  [Alfaro] During a meeting we held several days ago in Mexico 
City, an English-speaking nation said it had been directly 
pressured by other nations interested in garnering support for 
President Cesar Gaviria's candidacy.... [end recording] 
  Honduras, a nation recently visited by President Cesar 
Gaviria, expressed a great deal of liking for him, but it 
supports Niehaus because a prior commitment had already been 
made with him. 
  [Begin recording] [Protocol Director Ricardo Alonso Florez] 
We believe that in the first round the Central American nations 
will vote for the Costa Rican candidate, because he is Central 
American. Eventually, if there is a runoff election, a different 
decision could be made. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

