<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Forms New Movement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2703003294 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2301 GMT 26 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2703003294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Caracas, 26 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Today, upon being 
released from prison, Lieutenant Colonel Hugo Chavez, leader of 
the February 1992 coup attempt, announced he will form a 
political organization with rebel officers. The organization 
will be called the 2000 Revolutionary Bolivarian Movement 
[Movimiento Revolucionario Bolivariano 2000 -- a play on the 
name of Chavez's military movement, the 200 Revolutionary 
Bolivarian Movement, which emerged during the 4 February 1992 
coup attempt]. Chavez and 14 lower-ranking officers of the 
Venezuelan Army were released today. They were pardoned by 
President Rafael Caldera who is seeking reconciliation within 
the Armed Forces after the two 1992 coup attempts. 
  Dozens of supporters were waiting for Chavez when he was 
released at the military hospital were he had been held. He 
called on them to search for "the structural changes needed by 
the country" by forming a "wide national front." The Bolivarian 
Movement emerged after the 4 February 1992 military coup attempt 
against then-President Carlos Andres Perez on the grounds that 
Perez's economic adjustment policies were hurting the people. 
Meanwhile, thousands of other supporters gathered outside the 
San Carlos de Caracas military garrison to receive the 14 
officres who participated with Chavez in the coup against Perez, 
whom they accused of being "corrupt and a traitor." 
  Meanwhile, in Peru, General Francisco Visconti, one of the 
leaders of the 27 November 1992 military uprising, announced 
that at least 25 officers who took asylum in that country would 
return to Venezuela to surrender to military justice tomorrow, 
Sunday. With the release of Chavez and the 14 officers, the 
number of people granted presidential pardons, which are part of 
President Rafael Caldera's so-called "pacification policy," has 
risen to 60. With the exception of Gen. Visconti and the 46 
officers who took asylum in Peru, practically all of the leaders 
of the two coup attempts carried out two years ago have been 
released. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

