<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian President Elected OAS Secretary General </TI></H3>
<H4>   Gaviria Said To Have Needed Votes </H4>
<F P=102> PA2703034194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0130 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2703034194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "TV Today" newscast; passages within quotation </F>
marks recorded] 
  [Text] This evening, President Cesar Gaviria reportedly has 
the votes he needs to be elected OAS secretary general. 
Nevertheless, diplomatic sources do not believe President 
Gaviria will attain the needed absolute majority of votes during 
the first round of balloting by the OAS foreign ministers. 
  Tomorrow in Washington, 34 OAS member-nations will elect the 
seventh OAS secretary general. Colombian President Cesar 
Gaviria and Costa Rican Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus are the 
strongest candidates to replace Brazilian Joao Baena Soares as 
secretary general. 
  [Soares] "The most important thing for me is to complete my 
term in office by following the principles I established for 
myself from the very beginning." 
  On the eve of the elections, President Gaviria seems to be 
leading. Gaviria has the support of 16 countries, three more 
than his closest opponent -- Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus. 
  [Niehaus] "There are no blocs, and there are no secret 
commitments. We are only committed to ensuring respect for the 
OAS Charter." 
  To win the election, a candidate must receive an absolute 
majority of all votes cast -- in other words, 18 votes to keep 
the election from going to a second round. 
  [Former Colombian Foreign Minister Augusto Ramirez Ocampo] 
"If logic prevails, President Gaviria will win. Gaviria is a 
president, whereas Niehaus is a foreign minister. Gaviria also 
has the support of the largest countries on the continent." 
  Whoever the winner is, he will face the great challenge of 
reviving what many international analysts have described as a 
moribund organization. 
  [Analyst Diego Uribe Vargas, identified by caption] 
"Whenever 
it can, the United States disregards inter-American laws and 
principles, beginning with nonintervention, which is the first 
and foremost rule." 
  Experts say the new secretary general must bolster the OAS 
profile, making it stronger in the face of the U.S. Government. 
Many believe the OAS is excellent in theory, but that does not 
work in practice. 
  [Colombian Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin] "The new secretary 
general must have the discipline and commitment to work for 
everyone while excluding no one, especially those that need help 
the most." 
  This evening the Colombian foreign minister was working hard 
to ensure the votes of two undecided countries to lock up the 18 
votes needed by President Gaviria. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

