<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian President Elected OAS Secretary General </TI></H3>
<H4>   Niehaus Reacts to Defeat </H4>
<F P=102> PA2703174594 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1638 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2703174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Victor Alarcon, Caracol Colombian </F>
correspondent in Washington, DC, by unidentified reporter in 
Santa Fe de Bogota--live relay] 
  [Text] [Reporter] Victor Alarcon is our special 
correspondent. What happened with the speech by Costa Rican 
Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus? In Colombia, we are interested 
in learning the reaction. What happened? 
  [Alarcon] We are reporters, not diplomats; so we have to say 
the speech by the Nicaraguan foreign minister was rude. 
  [Reporter] Nicaraguan or Costa Rican? 
  [Alarcon] Pardon me, Costa Rican. 
  [Reporter] Niehaus. 
  [Alarcon] Mr. Niehaus. Pardon me. 
  [Reporter] That is fine. 
  [Alarcon] The speech was rude and arrogant. It was 
prompted, perhaps, by the agony of defeat. He called those 
countries colonies of an imperialist, namely, the United States. 
He said the best thing would be for the United States to 
handpick the new OAS secretary general. He withdrew irately 
from the hall, where the session continues. 
  The Argentine foreign minister spoke next to ask the 
assembly 
not to pay attention to the Costa Rican foreign minister's 
remarks, which were uttered in the agony of defeat. Those in 
attendance took that advice more seriously than Niehaus' 
statements. 
  The assembly continues. We will enter the assembly to be 
close to Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin, to carry her first 
reaction, given the fact she handled this campaign. She was 
truly the architect of the campaign of Cesar Gaviria Trujillo, 
who was elected the new OAS secretary general this morning. 

</TEXT>

