<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian President Elected OAS Secretary General </TI></H3>
<H4>   Colombian Minister Cited on Vote </H4>
<F P=102> PA2803024094 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0130 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2803024094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jesus Garzon from the "TV Today" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Cesar Gaviria's election as OAS secretary 
general did not come easily. There were dramatic moments that 
jeopardized it throughout the process. Foreign Minister Noemi 
Sanin had to use all of her strengths to win the OAS Secretariat 
General for Colombia: 
  [Begin Sanin recording] There was a time when Foreign 
Minister Niehaus was leading. There was tension all the time. 
We, however, remained confident we would win, and finally, we 
garnered an absolute majority. [end recording] 
  The days leading up to the election also featured dramatic 
moments that were witnessed by many, from President Gaviria at 
Narino Palace to the Colombian delegation in Washington headed 
by Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin. 
  [Begin Sanin recording] We contained our anxiety while we 
confronted challenging moments over the past few days. We held 
countless talks on a daily basis. There were concerns, 
questions, and ideas; there were... [pauses] We had to outline 
our policies on countless occasions. [end recording] 
  Now that Gaviria has been elected, the question is whether 
he, as the new OAS secretary general, will work to lift the 
suspension that this organization imposed on Cuba in 1962 
because of its political system. 
  [Begin Sanin recording] Colombia's current policy toward 
Cuba 
is sovereign and independent and is solely in keeping with 
Colombia's interests. President Gaviria's OAS policy should not 
follow Colombian policy but a policy common to the 34 nations 
that comprise the organization. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

