<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-American Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rio Group Negotiating Strategy for Miami Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2403021494 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
23 Mar 94 p 12--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2403021494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- The 12 Latin American and Caribbean 
countries that are Rio Group members are negotiating a joint 
strategy for multilateral meetings. The main objective is to 
agree on a position for the Summit of the Americas, due to be 
held in December in Miami (United States). According to 
Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim, the Rio Group foreign 
ministers should agree on common topics about commerce in the 
hemisphere, good management practices, the preservation of 
democracy, and social and environmental matters. The decision 
was announced on 22 March after the Rio Group countries' foreign 
ministers met for two days in Brasilia. 
  Amorim and Chilean Foreign Minister Carlos Figueroa Serrano 
took advantage of the meeting to sign an agreement for 
reciprocal protection and promotion of investments. Under the 
terms of the document, the two countries will permit the mutual 
free transfer of remittances. The agreement, however, includes 
reservations on six topics -- which were raised by Brazil -- to 
encourage Brazilian investment and restrict Chilean investment. 
  The foreign ministers also began the preparatory work for 
the 
Rio Group summit, scheduled for September in Rio de Janeiro. 
Celso Amorim said the Latin American diplomats also will seek a 
common position for a meeting with the European Union scheduled 
for 22 and 23 April in Sao Paulo. According to Amorim, Latin 
American countries will make joint exchange proposals to Russia, 
China, Japan, and other Asian countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

