<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Survey Shows Lula Still Leading in Campaign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2003182994 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
18 Mar 94 p 4--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2003182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in 
Portuguese on 18 March publishes on page 4 a 700-word 
unattributed article on the results of a survey showing current 
voting preferences for the different presidential candidates. 
  The article notes that the Brazilian Public Opinion and 
Statistics Institute, Ibope, interviewed 2,000 voters throughout 
the country between 18 and 22 February. According to the 
results of this poll, Luis Inacio Lula da Silva leads the pack 
with 29 percent of the votes; Paulo Maluf and Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso come in tied for second with 11 percent of the votes 
each; Leonel Brizola and Antonio Carlos Magalhaes are third with 
8 percent each; and Orestes Quercia and Alvaro Dias come in 
fourth with 4 percent of the votes. 
  The article also notes that Lula "has well-distributed 
support, in cities and rural areas, in the north and south, and 
among rich and poor." 
  The article also points out that Lula has a high rejection 
rate, while Cardoso has the lowest rejection rate among all 
presidential candidates, "which will become very important in 
the runoff election." 

</TEXT>

