<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian Media Cited on Controversy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2003201494 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1650 GMT 20 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2003201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bogota, 20 Mar (PL) -- Today, the newspaper EL 
TIEMPO said the Colombian Government is "absolutely silent... 
about Fidel Castro's reply," while EL ESPECTADOR published a 
poll that favors maintaining relations with Cuba. On Friday, EL 
TIEMPO published a report quoting a denial by the head of 
military intelligence, statements by the Cuban ambassador, and 
Caracol's version of an alleged telephone call from the Cuban 
president to [Colombian] Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin. 
  EL TIEMPO has been publishing reports, without any evidence, 
of an alleged meeting in Havana of Colombian guerrilla leaders 
and Bishop Nel Beltran, which both the Cuban Government and the 
bishop have denied. 
  EL ESPECTADOR newspaper's front page headline read "Nel On 
Fantasy Island." An article, covered on an inside page, reports 
the Disney Reservation Center in Florida confirmed that 
Monsignor Beltran stayed there between 24-25 January. 
  This newspaper also publishes on its front page a poll taken 
by the National Consulting Center, which shows that most of the 
440 people asked favor maintaining diplomatic relations with 
Cuba even if it turns out that the guerrilla summit in Havana 
was held. Of the people polled, 51 percent replied that 
diplomatic ties should not be severed, 30 percent said yes they 
should, and 19 percent said they did not know. 

</TEXT>

