<H3> <TI>   U.S. Army Forced To End Work in Costa Rica </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2603210594 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1936 GMT 26 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2603210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 26 Mar (PL) -- Costa Rican citizens today 
forced military personnel from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers 
to suspend road-repair work in the province of Alajuela. 
  According to a U.S. military spokesman, the work was 
suspended because of protests by residents of Legua de Pital, 
who blocked roads and demanded drains be built to avoid floods 
in the rainy season. The residents also warned that if troops 
continue their work without changing their construction 
techniques, they will organize more demonstrations to stop work 
by the Army Engineers. 
  Meanwhile, a communique issued by the U.S. Embassy in San 
Jose noted that U.S. soldiers will be remodeling and repairing 
several schools in the area over the next few days. The 
soldiers have been in the country since mid-January, 
participating in the annual "Caminos de Paz 1994" maneuvers. 

</TEXT>

