<H3> <TI>   Costa Rican Official Expresses `Regret' Over OAS Vote </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2703200894 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1709 GMT 27 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2703200894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 27 Mar (PL) -- Vice President German 
Serrano Pinto expressed regret today over the pressure exerted 
against several Central American and Caribbean small states to 
vote in favor of Colombian President Cesar Gaviria Trujillo for 
OAS secretary general. 
  In remarks made to a Costa Rican radio station from 
Washington where he headed his country's delegation at the 
voting, Serrano Pinto cited his sadness over the coercive 
methods applied against the members of the continental 
organization by a nation he declined to identify. 
  Costa Rica's government officials have not commented 
officially about the outcome of the election, which handed 
victory to the Colombian president with 20 votes cast for him 
and 14 for the Costa Rican candidate, Foreign Minister Bernd 
Niehaus. 
  As Costa Rican President Rafael Angel Calderon charged a few 
days ago, the United States resorted to pressuring the Caribbean 
and Central American states to hand the election to Gaviria, as 
that country regards Gaviria as "a candidate of hemispheric 
projection." 

</TEXT>

