<H3> <TI>   Costa Rican President-Elect Congratulates Gaviria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2803185494 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2803185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Speaking to this station, Costa Rican 
President-elect Jose Maria Figueres offered to cooperate with 
President Cesar Gaviria as the new OAS secretary general and 
said that Costa Rican Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus' reaction 
is purely personal. 
  [Begin recording] [Figueres] I congratulate President 
Gaviria 
and tell him that Costa Rica and other Latin American OAS member 
countries will always be willing to support worthwhile causes in 
Latin America. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Do you think the United States had 
its hand in the election? 
  [Figueres] There was a democratic process in which every 
country voted for the person it regarded as the best to 
consolidate leadership at the OAS. Therefore, I congratulate 
President Gaviria for his victory. 
  [Reporter] Your opinion on Foreign Minister Niehaus' remarks 
on the behavior of other countries' foreign ministers and the 
United States? 
  [Figueres] I am sure that Foreign Minister Niehaus spoke 
from 
a personal viewpoint and that his position does not represent 
the Costa Rican Government's position, let alone that of the 
government that will assume office on 8 May. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

