<H3> <TI>   Army Chief Opposes Voluntary Military Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2803045294 Tegucigalpa Telesistema Hondureno Television 
Network in Spanish 0130 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2803045294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tegucigalpa Telesistema Hondureno Television 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hector Ordonez from the "This Very Day" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Ironically, Armed Forces Commander Luis Alonso 
Discua has voiced opposition to President Carlos Roberto Reina's 
proposal to convert our military service into a voluntary one. 
Discua Elvir said the term voluntary can only be used to refer 
to going to the movies. The military commander also talked about 
the Armed Forces' ability to assist the public prosecutor in 
locating missing people. [passage indistinct] 
  Referring to the Armed Forces' budget, he noted it had been 
significantly reduced and now amounts to approximately $33 
million. Asked about Honduran Ondina Cea, who fled Iran because 
her father-in-law kept her in captivity, and the possibility of 
Iranian terrorists in Honduras, the officer said he did not have 
information on these matters. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Today, the 
Honduran's lawyer [words indistinct] charged there could be 
Iranian terrorists here. 
  [Discua] Yes, as I have already told you, I do not have any 
information on this. You have caught me a bit off guard. I did 
not get any information on this when I arrived. We will take the 
necessary measures once we have the appropriate information. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

