<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Expects No Changes After OAS Election </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2803192594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1707 GMT 28 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2803192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Managua, 28 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Today, the Nicaraguan 
Government ruled out any changes in relations between the "big 
and small" countries of the Americas following the dispute 
within the OAS over the election of its secretary general. The 
election of Colombian President Cesar Gaviria as OAS secretary 
general took place after reports that there was friction between 
the countries that supported the candidacy of Costa Rican 
Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus and those who supported the South 
American president. "Although Nicaragua maintained its support 
for the Costa Rican foreign minister, Gaviria's election will 
not alter relations," said a spokesman for the Nicaraguan 
Foreign Ministry. 
  North and South American countries supported the candidacy 
of 
the Colombian president, while Niehaus had the support of 
Central America and the Caribbean countries. According to the 
Foreign Ministry spokesman, Gaviria "is a very skillful and 
capable person because of his position." Gaviria will be leaving 
his post on 7 August when he turns it over to the president 
elected on 29 May in Colombia. 
  Today, the Nicaraguan press, on its front pages, emphasized 
the election of Gaviria as well as the frustration of Niehaus, 
who harshly criticized the United States for exerting pressure 
on countries that had committed their votes. Analysts had 
forecast that the battle over the secretary generalship of the 
hemispheric organization was a battle between the "large and 
small countries" of the Americas, and that no representative of 
Central America had ever occupied the post of OAS secretary 
general. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

