<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Panamanian Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2603171994 </F>
<F P=103> PA2603171994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the Panamanian elections 
scheduled for 8 May 1994. 
  Ernesto Perez Balladares, Democratic Revolutionary Party 
(PRD) presidential candidate, toured Arraijan District on 17 
March where the various communities 
greeted him. When asked about the foreign debt issue, he said 
"the debt was used for great works during President Torrijos' 
time, but the current government has handled it irresponsibly." 
(Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 17 
March 94) 
  While touring the corregimiento of Calidonia on 23 March, 
Perez Balladares said the other presidential candidates who are 
trying to unite the political force to undermine his 
presidential candidacy in the 8 May elections "will fail." Perez 
Balladares said his opponents were once united against Noriega, 
but now nothing is holding them together. (Panama City LA 
ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 24 March 94 p A1) 
  Ruben Dario Carles, Change 94 presidential candidate, has 
visited a mining company which is seeking to exploit gold 
deposits in Canazas, Veraguas Province. Carles then told the 
community he requested the company pay just salaries and conduct 
reforestation programs. (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in 
Spanish 2300 GMT 17 Mar 94) 
  Carles has vowed to defend the continuity of democracy and 
reduce energy rates. At a rally in Tole, Chiriqui Province, 
Carles promised he will revise energy rates. Carles said: "We 
must reduce energy rates; energy service is too expensive and 
inefficient." (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 21 March 94) 
  Carles is reportedly recovering from an accident he had on 
22 
March and therefore is limiting his political activities. 
Carles and a group of supporters fell from a balcony, and he 
reportedly twisted his ankle. Although his health was not 
endangered, Carles was advised to rest until his swollen ankle 
improves. Regarding this mishap, Carles concluded: "We have 
talked with other candidates to adopt appropriate measures to 
prevent people from continuing to live in old, rundown homes." 
(Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 23 
March 94) 
  Carles has requested the national government "to immediately 
suspend the renegotiation of the foreign debt with international 
banks, as it is unadvisable and extemporaneous," adding the 
government "should concentrate all of its efforts until 
September on attaining free elections which will pave the way 
for the new president and his team." (Panama City LA PRENSA in 
Spanish 24 March 94 p 2A) 
  Should she win the 8 May elections, Mireya Moscoso de 
Gruber, 
Arnulfista Party (PA) presidential candidate, has promised she 
would revise the minimum wage. De Gruber announced her intention 
after visiting several communities throughout the country where 
she found there is economic stagnation due to an increase in 
basic market products. De Gruber said: "Our government program 
establishes, after assuming the Presidency on 1 September, that 
we will conduct an in-depth and prompt study on the minimum 
wage. We must increase the minimum wage." (Panama City Circuito 
RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 17 March 94) 
  In statements to the newscast "Telemetro Reports," de Gruber 
has admitted that political forces have become polarized between 
the PRD and the PA. Given this situation, de Gruber reiterated 
her call to all political parties to form one single political 
coalition behind the PA so as to confront the PRD. De Gruber 
asked other candidates to decline their candidacies in her 
favor. Regarding electoral violence, de Gruber has said she 
hopes violence could be averted. (Panama City Telemetro 
Television Network in Spanish 1730 GMT 21 March 94) 
  The Solidarity Party will not heed other parties' call to 
form a civic alliance, Solidarity Party presidential candidate 
Samuel Lewis Galindo has warned. Members of the National 
Consensus Alliance, comprised by the Solidarity and National 
Unity Mission, have visited the Central Avenue area. Lewis 
Galindo said he does not favor a civic alliance. Galindo said: 
"The people are beginning to realize that in the fights between 
the candidates, we are the only ones who can attain the 
requisite national unity to fight poverty." (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 23 March 94) 
  Carlos Anel Cordero, Political Capsule columnist, reports 
Eduardo Vallarino, presidential candidate for the Christian 
Democratic Party, PDC, has addressed the National Federation of 
Business and Professional Women where he said the PDC government 
will insist on a more active role by women in administrative 
functions. Cordero adds all presidential candidates, except for 
the PA's Mireya Moscoso de Gruber, recently attended a meeting 
with the civic clubs during which they committed themselves to 
promote, respect, and strengthen civic values and morals. 
(Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 19 March 94 p 3A) 
  A 500-word article by Marco Julio de Obaldia states the PRD 
has one-third of the people's vote, "and this will be evident on 
8 May." De Obaldia writes "these votes were cultivated 
throughout 21 years," and most of the voters feel "they cannot 
go wrong by voting for the PRD." In conclusion, the writer urges 
the people to forget voting for the party of their choice, 
rather, to vote for the civic candidate who has "the greatest 
chance of winning," the only way to defeat the PRD candidate. 
(Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 19 March 94 p 8A) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

