<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Signs Agreement With Coca Growers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2803212594 La Paz Television Nacional Network in Spanish 
0300 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2803212594 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Television Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Government and coca growers representatives have 
signed an agreement to end the tense situation in the Chapare 
tropical region. The five-article document ratifies the two 
parties' desire to fight trafficking and to prevent the 
eradication of plantations. It confirms that the government will 
continue to look for and destroy laboratories but without 
destroying coca plantations. 
  Article 4 is the most controversial: It specifies that the 
government and coca-growers leaders will implement Articles 10, 
14 and 24 of Law 1008. The government is committed to implement 
alternative development programs. 
  It has also been agreed that mixed commissions will be 
created to deal with issues related to coca-leaf production. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Are you happy with 
the agreement? 
  [Unidentified coca growers leader] We believe there is an 
agreement, but we will only be happy when the terms of the 
agreement are complied with. [end recording] 
  The coca growers believe this agreement represents victory 
for them because the government has promised not to forcefully 
eradicate the sacred leaf. 
  [Begin unidentified coca growers leader recording] Forceful 
eradication without an alternative crop cannot flourish. [end 
recording] 
  The government believes the agreement will ensure peace and 
the implementation of alternative development in the 
coca-producing regions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

